Sure! Let's cover the reverse versions of the 3 classic traversals (inorder, preorder, postorder), each using one stack, and in a simple, easy-to-understand form.

ðŸŒ¿ Tree Traversals and Their Reverse Forms


| Traversal | Normal Order        | Reverse Order           |
| --------- | ------------------- | ----------------------- |
| Inorder   | Left â†’ Node â†’ Right | **Right â†’ Node â†’ Left** |
| Preorder  | Node â†’ Left â†’ Right | **Node â†’ Right â†’ Left** |
| Postorder | Left â†’ Right â†’ Node | **Right â†’ Left â†’ Node** |


Now letâ€™s implement reverse versions using one stack.


âœ… 1. Reverse Inorder Iterator (Right â†’ Node â†’ Left)


class ReverseInorderIterator implements TreeIterator {
    private Stack<TreeNode> stack = new Stack<>();
    private TreeNode current;

    public ReverseInorderIterator(TreeNode root) {
        current = root;
    }

    @Override
    public boolean hasNext() {
        return current != null || !stack.isEmpty();
    }

    @Override
    public Integer next() {
        while (current != null) {
            stack.push(current);
            current = current.right;  // go right first
        }

        TreeNode node = stack.pop();
        current = node.left;  // then go left
        return node.val;
    }
}


âœ… 2. Reverse Preorder Iterator (Node â†’ Right â†’ Left)


class ReversePreorderIterator implements TreeIterator {
    private Stack<TreeNode> stack = new Stack<>();

    public ReversePreorderIterator(TreeNode root) {
        if (root != null) stack.push(root);
    }

    @Override
    public boolean hasNext() {
        return !stack.isEmpty();
    }

    @Override
    public Integer next() {
        TreeNode node = stack.pop();

        // Push left after right so that left is processed last
        if (node.left != null) stack.push(node.left);
        if (node.right != null) stack.push(node.right);

        return node.val;
    }
}



âœ… 3. Reverse Postorder Iterator (Right â†’ Left â†’ Node)
This is the reverse of the true postorder: youâ€™ll simulate it and reverse the output if needed â€” but if you want to generate the reverse postorder directly, you can simulate it like so:


class ReversePostorderIterator implements TreeIterator {
    private Stack<TreeNode> stack = new Stack<>();
    private TreeNode lastVisited = null;
    private TreeNode current;

    public ReversePostorderIterator(TreeNode root) {
        current = root;
    }

    @Override
    public boolean hasNext() {
        return current != null || !stack.isEmpty();
    }

    @Override
    public Integer next() {
        while (current != null) {
            stack.push(current);
            current = current.right;  // go right first
        }

        TreeNode peekNode = stack.peek();

        if (peekNode.left != null && lastVisited != peekNode.left) {
            current = peekNode.left;
            return next();
        }

        stack.pop();
        lastVisited = peekNode;
        return peekNode.val;
    }
}



// using two stacks


import java.util.*;

class ReversePostorderIterator implements Iterator<Integer> {
    private Stack<Integer> output = new Stack<>();

    public ReversePostorderIterator(TreeNode root) {
        if (root == null) return;

        Stack<TreeNode> stack1 = new Stack<>();
        Stack<TreeNode> stack2 = new Stack<>();
        stack1.push(root);

        while (!stack1.isEmpty()) {
            TreeNode node = stack1.pop();
            stack2.push(node); // node is processed after children

            // To get RLN: push LEFT first, then RIGHT
            if (node.right != null) stack1.push(node.right);
            if (node.left != null) stack1.push(node.left);
        }

        while (!stack2.isEmpty()) {
            output.push(stack2.pop().val);
        }
    }

    @Override
    public boolean hasNext() {
        return !output.isEmpty();
    }

    @Override
    public Integer next() {
        if (!hasNext()) throw new NoSuchElementException();
        return output.pop();
    }
}
